rning South African Participation -- tJuan Antonio Samaranch’s Score Sheet: Revenue Generation and the Olympic Movement, 1980–2001 -- tThe Future of the Olympic Games -- t“To Construct a Better and More Peaceful World” or “War Minus the Shooting”?: The Olympic Movement’s Second Century -- tWorks Cited in Part II -- tGlossary of Terms -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Olympic Games have had two lives—the first lasted for a millennium with celebrations every four years at Olympia to honour the god Zeus. The second has blossomed over the past century, from a simple start in Athens in 1896 to a dazzling return to Greece in 2004. Onward to the Olympics provides both an overview and an array of insights into aspects of the Games’ history. Leading North American archaeologists and historians of sport explore the origins of the Games, compare the ancient and the modern, discuss the organization and financing of such massive athletic festivals, and examine the participation ,or the troubling lack of it, by women. Onward to the Olympics bridges the historical divide between the ancient and the modern and concludes with a thought-provoking final essay that attempts to predict the future of the Olympics over the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJeux olympiques de l'AntiquitéxHistoire. 0aJeux olympiques de l'AntiquitéxHistoire. 0aJeux olympiquesxHistoire. 0aOlympic games (Ancient)xHistory. 0aOlympicsxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aSports & Recreation. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Olympics & Paralympics.2bisacsh1 aAjootian, Aileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarney, Robert K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristesen, Paul, econtribu